Manhattan College, Broadway at the N.E. corner of 131st Street, showing also the north side of 131st Street from Broadway to Old Broadway. The college has abandoned this building and moved to the northernmost part of the Bronx; the present building will soon be torn down, and the lot will be vacant as late as 1936.
April, 1926.

622 West 131st Street, south side, between Broadway and Twelfth avenue. This is a three-story frame house. The first story has a brick front and the two upper stories are of wood.
1932.
J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.
Negative No. 314

60-66 Old Broadway, at, adjoining, and south of the S.W. corner of West 131st Street. Nos. 64 and 66 are both frame houses.
1932.
J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.
Negative No. 334.

Broadway, east side, north from W. 131st Street, showing at the N.E. corner of that point, a cleared area and upon which formerly stood Manhattan College. To the north of same is the Nash Co. garage and sales room occupying the balance of this block front to 133rd Street. Note that W. 132nd Street is not cut thru this block.
View No. 2 is a south eastward view across the aforementioned feature. On the right margin of this view appears the steel pillars of the elevated section of the I.R.T. subway line.
April 1, 1938.
Views 1 a nd 2
P.L. Sperr

Old Broadway, north from W. 131st to 133rd Streets, showing buildings on the easterly side of same. The low 2 story structure at the right is of frame construction and bears No. 77. At the corner of this block and only partially seen on the right margin is the Manhattanville Day Nursery. View No. 2 being in a southward direction from W. 132nd Street shows this feature. Note the empty lots on the opposite side. Beyond the latter and located at the S.W. corner of 131st Street are two more frame buildings with sloping roofs that bear No's 64 and 66.

April 1, 1938
